WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.770 --> 00:00:02.380
MALE SPEAKER: And
now, please join me

00:00:02.380 --> 00:00:07.370
in welcoming Thunder Levin,
the writer of "Sharknado."

00:00:07.370 --> 00:00:08.060
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:08.060 --> 00:00:09.630
THUNDER LEVIN: Thank you, David.

00:00:09.630 --> 00:00:12.370
Thank all of you
for joining me today

00:00:12.370 --> 00:00:17.160
for this most
important presentation.

00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:20.080
Since the beginning of
history, human society

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:23.620
has been held together by
a common language and frame

00:00:23.620 --> 00:00:27.480
of reference provided by the
shared communal experience

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:29.354
of storytelling.

00:00:29.354 --> 00:00:30.770
From Neanderthals
sitting around a

00:00:30.770 --> 00:00:33.810
campfire, to the
classic Greek plays,

00:00:33.810 --> 00:00:37.100
to the commoners
assembling for Shakespeare,

00:00:37.100 --> 00:00:39.440
to the works of
Hitchcock and Spielberg

00:00:39.440 --> 00:00:41.730
playing for packed
movie theaters,

00:00:41.730 --> 00:00:44.400
those shared communal
experiences are

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:46.820
what held our society together.

00:00:46.820 --> 00:00:50.760
They gave people from disparate
backgrounds, cultures,

00:00:50.760 --> 00:00:54.410
and socioeconomic classes
a common framework

00:00:54.410 --> 00:00:56.200
and understanding.

00:00:56.200 --> 00:00:59.410
Just a generation ago,
every man, woman, and child

00:00:59.410 --> 00:01:03.240
in America was required to
watch the Tonight Show starring

00:01:03.240 --> 00:01:06.410
Johnny Carson so that they would
know what everyone was talking

00:01:06.410 --> 00:01:08.840
about the next morning.

00:01:08.840 --> 00:01:12.280
But as the technological
revolution of the internet

00:01:12.280 --> 00:01:16.690
has fractured the way we consume
media, with people watching

00:01:16.690 --> 00:01:21.330
what they want, when they want,
where they want, how they want,

00:01:21.330 --> 00:01:24.690
that water cooler
moment has been lost.

00:01:24.690 --> 00:01:26.500
If half your friends
cover their ears

00:01:26.500 --> 00:01:28.920
when you start talking about
Game of Thrones on Monday

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:31.300
mornings because they
haven't seen it yet,

00:01:31.300 --> 00:01:33.990
you understand what
I'm talking about.

00:01:33.990 --> 00:01:37.060
And with that fracturing,
with that loss of the shared

00:01:37.060 --> 00:01:40.700
communal storytelling
experience, and the resulting

00:01:40.700 --> 00:01:44.910
loss of a common language, our
society began to break down.

00:01:44.910 --> 00:01:49.090
Friends no longer spoke face to
face, or even on the telephone.

00:01:49.090 --> 00:01:52.300
Instead, we poked each
other electronically.

00:01:52.300 --> 00:01:54.310
People no longer gather
together in groups,

00:01:54.310 --> 00:01:57.590
but instead posted
in chat rooms,

00:01:57.590 --> 00:02:01.160
without ever truly knowing
who they conversed with.

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:03.470
And conversation itself
became a lost art,

00:02:03.470 --> 00:02:07.530
giving way to texts
and emoticons.

00:02:07.530 --> 00:02:10.930
And so our civilization careened
toward self destruction.

00:02:13.770 --> 00:02:18.560
Into this pre-apocalyptic
decline in July of 2013

00:02:18.560 --> 00:02:21.510
came the most
unlikely of saviors.

00:02:21.510 --> 00:02:25.390
When a ridiculous TV movie
about a tornado of sharks

00:02:25.390 --> 00:02:28.640
premiered on the SciFi channel,
the most surprising thing

00:02:28.640 --> 00:02:29.810
happened.

00:02:29.810 --> 00:02:33.630
Our society as a whole
ground to a halt,

00:02:33.630 --> 00:02:36.430
and billions and billions
of people all over the world

00:02:36.430 --> 00:02:42.550
flocked to Twitter
and began to converse.

00:02:42.550 --> 00:02:46.750
Our modern gods, also
known as celebrities,

00:02:46.750 --> 00:02:48.190
join the conversation.

00:02:48.190 --> 00:02:52.480
Such luminaries as Elizabeth
Banks, Will Wheaton,

00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:56.590
Patton Oswalt, Olivia
Wilde, Judah Friedlander,

00:02:56.590 --> 00:02:58.850
Damon Lindelof, the
producer of LOST,

00:02:58.850 --> 00:03:01.740
and even Mia Farrow
and Philip Roth

00:03:01.740 --> 00:03:06.170
all tweeted about "Sharknado".

00:03:06.170 --> 00:03:09.060
During the initial broadcast,
the Sharknado hashtag

00:03:09.060 --> 00:03:12.790
generated over 5,000
tweets per minute.

00:03:12.790 --> 00:03:16.150
That night, the movie became
the first shared communal

00:03:16.150 --> 00:03:20.280
storytelling experience
of the internet age.

00:03:20.280 --> 00:03:23.910
And by the next morning,
the water cooler moment

00:03:23.910 --> 00:03:28.760
had been reinvented and society
had a new common language.

00:03:28.760 --> 00:03:31.180
Therefore in summary,
I'm sure you'll

00:03:31.180 --> 00:03:33.770
agree that I'm not exaggerating
when I suggest what

00:03:33.770 --> 00:03:37.800
the humble sci-fi movie
"Sharknado" has saved

00:03:37.800 --> 00:03:39.930
civilization as we know it.

00:03:39.930 --> 00:03:42.036
Thank you for your time.

00:03:42.036 --> 00:03:45.382
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:47.245 --> 00:03:48.620
MALE SPEAKER: All
right, Thunder.

00:03:48.620 --> 00:03:49.380
Well, thank you.

00:03:49.380 --> 00:03:51.770
It's hard to know how
to follow that up.

00:03:51.770 --> 00:03:54.460
THUNDER LEVIN: The
key to "Sharknado"

00:03:54.460 --> 00:03:56.620
