00:03:56.620 --> 00:03:58.000
So I like to just--

00:04:01.230 --> 00:04:03.480
MALE SPEAKER: So while we
were sitting there watching

00:04:03.480 --> 00:04:07.400
the trailer, you mentioned
that that opening scene, which

00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:10.390
was cinematically criticized--

00:04:10.390 --> 00:04:12.250
THUNDER LEVIN: Yes,
even in our promo,

00:04:12.250 --> 00:04:15.290
they pointed out that the
opening scene with the mafioso

00:04:15.290 --> 00:04:17.476
had nothing to do with
the rest of the movie.

00:04:17.476 --> 00:04:18.850
And that shouldn't
be surprising,

00:04:18.850 --> 00:04:21.620
because I didn't write it.

00:04:21.620 --> 00:04:26.490
I had one opening shot of a
Mexican fisherman on his boat

00:04:26.490 --> 00:04:31.120
looking up at this huge
wave of sharks and saying,

00:04:31.120 --> 00:04:35.400
"necessito un barko mas grande,"
which obviously you can tell

00:04:35.400 --> 00:04:38.441
is, "I'm going to
need a bigger boat."

00:04:38.441 --> 00:04:40.815
And then the wave crashed over
him and the sharks ate him

00:04:40.815 --> 00:04:42.310
and that was it.

00:04:42.310 --> 00:04:43.510
And it was just one shot.

00:04:43.510 --> 00:04:45.679
But when the director
came to shoot it,

00:04:45.679 --> 00:04:47.220
this being a low
budget film and all,

00:04:47.220 --> 00:04:50.060
he couldn't justify
renting a boat

00:04:50.060 --> 00:04:52.890
and going out on the water,
and bringing the whole crew

00:04:52.890 --> 00:04:55.410
and spending a day
just for one shot.

00:04:55.410 --> 00:04:59.200
So he invented the mafioso
scene sort of on the spot.

00:04:59.200 --> 00:05:01.810
And they just-- and I when
I watched the premiere

00:05:01.810 --> 00:05:03.542
I hadn't seen the film.

00:05:03.542 --> 00:05:06.000
I was watching at the beginning
of the movie thinking, what

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.860
the fuck is going on?

00:05:08.860 --> 00:05:11.469
MALE SPEAKER: You're going to
edit that out in post, right?

00:05:11.469 --> 00:05:13.010
THUNDER LEVIN: Oh,
you didn't tell me

00:05:13.010 --> 00:05:14.134
I had to watch my language.

00:05:16.840 --> 00:05:20.580
MALE SPEAKER: So how did you
come to write "Sharknado"?

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:23.460
THUNDER LEVIN: You ask that
like it's an odd thing.

00:05:23.460 --> 00:05:27.420
It's funny, I had done a film
for the Asylum, the production

00:05:27.420 --> 00:05:31.272
company, called "American
Warships," which

00:05:31.272 --> 00:05:32.230
they liked quite a bit.

00:05:32.230 --> 00:05:34.850
It was one of their more
successful productions.

00:05:34.850 --> 00:05:37.080
And so they asked me
what I wanted to do next.

00:05:37.080 --> 00:05:39.305
And I had a couple of things.

00:05:39.305 --> 00:05:40.180
I wasn't really sure.

00:05:40.180 --> 00:05:44.580
And they said we want you to do
this movie called Shark Storm.

00:05:44.580 --> 00:05:46.520
And I was like, why?

00:05:46.520 --> 00:05:50.450
Haven't we had
enough shark movies?

00:05:50.450 --> 00:05:52.950
And so I turned it
down, especially

00:05:52.950 --> 00:05:55.770
knowing that the Asylum has a
habit of playing their movies

00:05:55.770 --> 00:05:57.300
completely straight.

00:05:57.300 --> 00:05:59.370
And I knew with
the budget that it

00:05:59.370 --> 00:06:02.450
would have there was no way
it was not going to be cheesy,

00:06:02.450 --> 00:06:06.442
and people would laugh
at it instead of with it.

00:06:06.442 --> 00:06:08.150
And so I was developing
some other ideas.

00:06:08.150 --> 00:06:10.790
And then like a month
later they came back to me

00:06:10.790 --> 00:06:14.980
and they said, forget Shark
Storm, it's Sharknado.

00:06:14.980 --> 00:06:18.270
And I was like, what do sharks
have to do with the North

00:06:18.270 --> 00:06:20.760
Atlantic Treaty Organization?

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:22.860
Because I heard Shark NATO.

00:06:22.860 --> 00:06:24.420
And he said, no, no, no.

00:06:24.420 --> 00:06:26.980
Sharknado, a tornado
full of sharks.

00:06:26.980 --> 00:06:29.230
And I said, oh, well, that's
the most ridiculous thing

00:06:29.230 --> 00:06:30.700
I've ever heard of.

00:06:30.700 --> 00:06:32.980
And as long as I can
do it that way, I'm in.

00:06:32.980 --> 00:06:37.190
And they recognized, despite
never doing tongue in cheek,

00:06:37.190 --> 00:06:39.260
that something called
Sharknado pretty much had

00:06:39.260 --> 00:06:42.090
to be handled that way.

00:06:42.090 --> 00:06:43.570
And so then I just
had fun with it

00:06:43.570 --> 00:06:48.252
and never expected
anything to come of it,

00:06:48.252 --> 00:06:49.710
or I would have
directed it myself,

00:06:49.710 --> 00:06:51.810
because I was originally
attached to direct it.

00:06:54.900 --> 00:06:58.410
And then something
strange happened.

00:06:58.410 --> 00:07:03.260
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah, so was the--
could I get the screen up here?

00:07:03.260 --> 00:07:05.870
Was that response really
overwhelming for you?

00:07:05.870 --> 00:07:09.910
Did you have any idea anything
like this could happen?

00:07:09.910 --> 00:07:11.410
THUNDER LEVIN: It's
funny, because I

00:07:11.410 --> 00:07:15.510
had I had joked with a friend--
after I wrote the script, I'd

00:07:15.510 --> 00:07:19.300
finished the script like the
summer before, summer of 2012,

00:07:19.300 --> 00:07:21.190
and then went on to
do another project.

00:07:21.190 --> 00:07:26.560
Because I directed another film
in the jungles of Costa Rica

00:07:26.560 --> 00:07:29.470
at the same time the Sharknado
was being shot in LA.

00:07:29.470 --> 00:07:32.110
But I remember joking to a
friend that someday, goddammit,

00:07:32.110 --> 00:07:33.420
I'm going to win an Oscar.

00:07:33.420 --> 00:07:35.160
And even then all
anyone will want

00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:37.326
to talk to me about is this
crazy thing I've written

00:07:37.326 --> 00:07:38.544
called "Sharknado."

00:07:38.544 --> 00:07:39.960
MALE SPEAKER:
Little did you know.

00:07:39.960 --> 00:07:42.570
THUNDER LEVIN:
Little did I know.

00:07:42.570 --> 00:07:46.560
We had a hint that something
might be brewing about a week

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:49.130
beforehand.

00:07:49.130 --> 00:07:53.120
The commercials seemed to
be getting good response.

00:07:53.120 --> 00:07:56.950
And the press was
starting to pick up on it.

00:07:56.950 --> 00:08:00.510
I did a really fun
interview with io9

00:08:00.510 --> 00:08:02.380
where they asked some
very serious questions

00:08:02.380 --> 00:08:06.760
and I answered in the most
serious manner possible.

00:08:06.760 --> 00:08:09.060
And then July 4 came
around, and a couple

00:08:09.060 --> 00:08:13.229
of friends who had gone to
different July 4 parties

00:08:13.229 --> 00:08:14.770
called me up and
said that people had

00:08:14.770 --> 00:08:16.760
been talking about "Sharknado."

00:08:16.760 --> 00:08:18.280
And it hadn't aired yet.

00:08:18.280 --> 00:08:20.680
And I was like, they're
talking about "Sharknado"?

00:08:20.680 --> 00:08:26.080
How can that-- and then things
like this started happening.

00:08:26.080 --> 00:08:28.530
Yeah, but no, we
thought maybe it might

00:08:28.530 --> 00:08:31.330
turn into a little cult hit.

00:08:31.330 --> 00:08:35.280
But when it blew up on Twitter
that night it was just surreal.

00:08:35.280 --> 00:08:38.030
We had-- nobody expected that.

00:08:38.030 --> 00:08:40.710
We went on Twitter
expecting 100 people.

00:08:40.710 --> 00:08:42.929
And 10 would be asking
us serious questions.

00:08:42.929 --> 00:08:45.370
And 90 would be telling
us how much we sucked.

00:08:45.370 --> 00:08:47.760
And that would be it.

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:49.890
And then we tried to
get into the tweet,

00:08:49.890 --> 00:08:52.420
and you just couldn't get
in, because there were just

00:08:52.420 --> 00:08:54.510
so many tweets coming in.

00:08:54.510 --> 00:08:57.030
And then the celebrities
started getting in on it.

00:08:57.030 --> 00:08:59.040
And the most surreal
part of the night for me

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:01.750
was trading tweets
with Damon Lindelof,

00:09:01.750 --> 00:09:08.000
who was the producer of "Lost"
and also co-wrote "Prometheus."

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.240
He's the one who took
Prometheus from being

00:09:10.240 --> 00:09:12.820
a true prequel to
"Alien" and turned it

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:16.050
into a not quite prequel.

00:09:16.050 --> 00:09:18.160
And so I ended up
trading tweets with him

00:09:18.160 --> 00:09:19.640
because he said
that he was going

00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:21.580
to write the sequel
to "Sharknado"

00:09:21.580 --> 00:09:27.100
and have it done by the time
"Sharknado" was off the air.

00:09:27.100 --> 00:09:32.220
And so I countered that I hoped
he would let me be involved.

00:09:32.220 --> 00:09:33.990
But I thought the
rather than a sequel,

00:09:33.990 --> 00:09:37.420
we should do a prequel,
only not quite.

00:09:37.420 --> 00:09:39.870
And he responded touche.

00:09:39.870 --> 00:09:43.100
And that just made my night.

00:09:43.100 --> 00:09:46.700
MALE SPEAKER: And since then
we've had the nado added--

00:09:46.700 --> 00:09:48.520
THUNDER LEVIN: Nado is
added to everything.

00:09:48.520 --> 00:09:51.060
MALE SPEAKER: Did you ever
expect there to be a Twerknado?

00:09:51.060 --> 00:09:51.730
THUNDER LEVIN: Is there?

00:09:51.730 --> 00:09:52.830
MALE SPEAKER: There
is a Twerknado.

00:09:52.830 --> 00:09:54.300
THUNDER LEVIN: Well,
depending on who's doing it,

00:09:54.300 --> 00:09:55.174
I'd like to see that.

00:09:59.020 --> 00:10:02.660
MALE SPEAKER: So how do you
come up with this stuff?

00:10:02.660 --> 00:10:06.069
I mean, do you wake up and
say, oh, yeah of course.

00:10:06.069 --> 00:10:07.360
I know how to fix that problem.

00:10:07.360 --> 00:10:12.375
A guy will jump into a flying
shark with a chainsaw, like--

00:10:12.375 --> 00:10:14.750
THUNDER LEVIN: See, you say
that like it's something odd.

00:10:14.750 --> 00:10:18.260
It just makes
perfect sense to me.

00:10:18.260 --> 00:10:20.330
MALE SPEAKER: Well,
give us something--

00:10:20.330 --> 00:10:22.538
THUNDER LEVIN: What do you
find illogical about that?

00:10:22.538 --> 00:10:25.260
How would you handle
the situation?

00:10:25.260 --> 00:10:27.360
MALE SPEAKER: This is why
you're the interviewee

00:10:27.360 --> 00:10:28.785
and I'm the interviewer.

00:10:28.785 --> 00:10:30.910
THUNDER LEVIN: You know,
people always ask me that.

00:10:30.910 --> 00:10:33.560
I don't know, I mean,
I don't do drugs.

00:10:33.560 --> 00:10:36.010
I wasn't drunk or
high when I wrote it.

00:10:36.010 --> 00:10:40.720
It's a matter of
taking a disaster

00:10:40.720 --> 00:10:42.800
movie, a standard
disaster movie,

00:10:42.800 --> 00:10:45.370
and following all the
rules of screenwriting.

00:10:45.370 --> 00:10:47.030
But when you get
to the point where

00:10:47.030 --> 00:10:49.440
people say that's
not believable,

00:10:49.440 --> 00:10:53.990
you just keep going,
because it's "Sharknado."

00:10:53.990 --> 00:10:57.710
And we could justify
just about anything.

00:10:57.710 --> 00:11:01.580
Now I should say that
in the first two films,

00:11:01.580 --> 00:11:05.210
and the first 80% of the third
film, everything that happens

00:11:05.210 --> 00:11:08.220
is at least
theoretically possible.

00:11:08.220 --> 00:11:11.450
Highly unlikely, I'll
give you, but at least

00:11:11.450 --> 00:11:13.690
theoretically possible.

00:11:13.690 --> 00:11:17.070
Once the sharks went into
space in the third one,

00:11:17.070 --> 00:11:18.465
we sort of lost that.

00:11:18.465 --> 00:11:20.340
MALE SPEAKER: You could
feel your credibility

00:11:20.340 --> 00:11:21.400
kind of went out the window.

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:23.316
THUNDER LEVIN: The thing
is that in the script

00:11:23.316 --> 00:11:26.460
for the third one, when the
sharks were blown into space,

00:11:26.460 --> 00:11:29.040
they're blown up
with a lot of water.

00:11:29.040 --> 00:11:32.040
So when they get into
zero g, each shark

00:11:32.040 --> 00:11:34.450
is in a globule of
water floating through.

00:11:34.450 --> 00:11:36.889
So it still made sense.

00:11:36.889 --> 00:11:39.180
But when the director shot
it, he didn't-- I don't know

00:11:39.180 --> 00:11:41.346
whether he made the choice
or the effects department

00:11:41.346 --> 00:11:42.920
couldn't do it,
but at some point,

00:11:42.920 --> 00:11:44.620
the globules of water were lost.

00:11:44.620 --> 00:11:46.550
MALE SPEAKER: That's
a loss for humanity.

00:11:46.550 --> 00:11:51.890
THUNDER LEVIN: Yeah, so it
would have been scientifically--

00:11:51.890 --> 00:11:53.660
MALE SPEAKER: But
it makes sense.

00:11:53.660 --> 00:11:55.500
THUNDER LEVIN: The
Jet Propulsion Lab,

00:11:55.500 --> 00:11:57.970
after the first movie,
the Jet Propulsion Lab

00:11:57.970 --> 00:12:03.840
put out an article that was
supposed to debunk "Sharknado."

00:12:03.840 --> 00:12:07.180
And all they really
did was end up saying,

00:12:07.180 --> 00:12:10.700
well, yeah, it is
possible, we just

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:12.480
don't think it's
going to happen.

00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:14.230
MALE SPEAKER: You'd
think those guys would

00:12:14.230 --> 00:12:16.944
be working on something else.

00:12:16.944 --> 00:12:19.110
THUNDER LEVIN: Well, they
got to do important stuff.

00:12:19.110 --> 00:12:20.120
MALE SPEAKER: That's
true, that's true.

00:12:20.120 --> 00:12:21.530
Nothing could be more important.

00:12:21.530 --> 00:12:22.905
THUNDER LEVIN:
That's what I say.

