00:23:20.200 --> 00:23:22.537
So, if you could go back--

00:23:22.537 --> 00:23:24.870
THUNDER LEVIN: See now, if
we had planned this properly,

00:23:24.870 --> 00:23:27.090
you would have told me
what you're about to say

00:23:27.090 --> 00:23:29.550
and I would have started
saying it before you asked me.

00:23:29.550 --> 00:23:30.500
MALE SPEAKER: What
a lost opportunity.

00:23:30.500 --> 00:23:31.708
THUNDER LEVIN: Yeah, oh well.

00:23:31.708 --> 00:23:33.450
I'm sorry, go ahead.

00:23:33.450 --> 00:23:35.950
MALE SPEAKER: I'm going to try
again to ask my question now.

00:23:35.950 --> 00:23:38.015
THUNDER LEVIN: I'm sorry.

00:23:38.015 --> 00:23:40.640
MALE SPEAKER: So if you could go
back in time to when you first

00:23:40.640 --> 00:23:44.989
arrived in LA, what career
advice would you give yourself?

00:23:44.989 --> 00:23:45.780
THUNDER LEVIN: Wow.

00:23:49.850 --> 00:23:53.720
You know, people now, film
students and wannabe writers

00:23:53.720 --> 00:23:56.530
keep asking me for advice.

00:23:56.530 --> 00:24:01.330
And I'm really not sure what
the answer is because everything

00:24:01.330 --> 00:24:03.650
I did seemed to make sense.

00:24:03.650 --> 00:24:06.540
It just took a lot
longer to get where

00:24:06.540 --> 00:24:10.590
I wanted to be than I expected.

00:24:10.590 --> 00:24:13.040
I don't have any good advice.

00:24:13.040 --> 00:24:15.541
MALE SPEAKER: Well, at least
you got where you wanted to be.

00:24:15.541 --> 00:24:16.748
THUNDER LEVIN: Well, not yet.

00:24:16.748 --> 00:24:18.068
I haven't directed "Star Wars."

00:24:18.068 --> 00:24:20.730
MALE SPEAKER: OK, well, close.

00:24:20.730 --> 00:24:23.420
THUNDER LEVIN: Working on it.

00:24:23.420 --> 00:24:26.270
MALE SPEAKER: So what
other projects are brewing

00:24:26.270 --> 00:24:28.280
in the moment of Thunder Levin?

00:24:28.280 --> 00:24:32.490
THUNDER LEVIN: Well, I'm
pitching two TV series.

00:24:32.490 --> 00:24:34.890
One is a serious,
post-apocalyptic-- not

00:24:34.890 --> 00:24:36.810
post-apocalyptic, apocalyptic.

00:24:36.810 --> 00:24:38.400
It's the end of the
world is happening

00:24:38.400 --> 00:24:40.920
sort of in slow motion.

00:24:40.920 --> 00:24:43.370
And my agent has
that out right now.

00:24:43.370 --> 00:24:46.200
I've got another series
that's more like "Sharknado."

00:24:46.200 --> 00:24:48.560
It's sort of tongue in cheek.

00:24:48.560 --> 00:24:53.250
I've been describing
it as "Star Trek" meets

00:24:53.250 --> 00:24:55.620
"One Flew Over the Cuckoo's
Nest" in a submarine.

00:24:58.290 --> 00:25:03.310
Basically a group of escaped
US Navy mental patients

00:25:03.310 --> 00:25:06.700
hijack an experimental
deep diving submarine

00:25:06.700 --> 00:25:08.910
and are then the only
people in a position

00:25:08.910 --> 00:25:11.260
to save the world
when mysteriously

00:25:11.260 --> 00:25:14.290
the surface of the oceans
start freezing over.

00:25:14.290 --> 00:25:16.280
And they discover all
sorts of strange worlds

00:25:16.280 --> 00:25:17.820
at the bottom of the sea.

00:25:17.820 --> 00:25:19.730
And eventually, they
discover that aliens

00:25:19.730 --> 00:25:22.160
are terraforming our plan
and they have to save us.

00:25:22.160 --> 00:25:24.370
But that takes a while.

00:25:24.370 --> 00:25:26.670
MALE SPEAKER: So once again,
staying within the bounds

00:25:26.670 --> 00:25:27.450
of the possible.

00:25:27.450 --> 00:25:29.940
THUNDER LEVIN: Yeah.

00:25:29.940 --> 00:25:33.930
MALE SPEAKER: And I've
heard there's been

00:25:33.930 --> 00:25:37.120
talk of a "Sharknado" musical.

00:25:37.120 --> 00:25:39.030
THUNDER LEVIN:
Well, I'll tell you,

00:25:39.030 --> 00:25:41.630
ever since the
first movie blew up

00:25:41.630 --> 00:25:45.390
and we started talking
about a sequel, myself

00:25:45.390 --> 00:25:47.520
and the director,
we've both been pushing

00:25:47.520 --> 00:25:49.730
to do Sharknado the musical.

00:25:49.730 --> 00:25:53.130
My suggestion for the
title for the second one

00:25:53.130 --> 00:25:55.810
was Sharknado 2,
The Great White Way.

00:25:58.460 --> 00:26:00.650
And they didn't go for it.

00:26:00.650 --> 00:26:05.210
And then like right around
when the third movie came out,

00:26:05.210 --> 00:26:07.980
the powers that be started
talking about maybe

00:26:07.980 --> 00:26:10.870
we should turn this
into a Broadway musical.

00:26:10.870 --> 00:26:13.140
And so the director and I
got very excited about that.

00:26:13.140 --> 00:26:16.200
And then nothing has
really come of that.

00:26:16.200 --> 00:26:18.770
And then about a
week or two ago I

00:26:18.770 --> 00:26:25.030
was-- a fellow classmate,
Richard Tucksmith,

00:26:25.030 --> 00:26:26.960
appeared out of
nowhere, and said hey,

00:26:26.960 --> 00:26:31.570
are you going to this
musical called Shark Attack?

00:26:31.570 --> 00:26:34.650
It's the unauthorized
parody of "Sharknado."

00:26:34.650 --> 00:26:37.340
And I had not heard about
it, but I got my tickets

00:26:37.340 --> 00:26:39.150
and I went.

00:26:39.150 --> 00:26:40.450
And it was a staged reading.

00:26:40.450 --> 00:26:42.050
They were trying
to get investors.

00:26:42.050 --> 00:26:43.770
But this show was great.

00:26:43.770 --> 00:26:45.040
I mean, it was funny.

00:26:45.040 --> 00:26:46.100
It was well written.

00:26:46.100 --> 00:26:49.480
The songs were catchy.

00:26:49.480 --> 00:26:53.000
And so I emailed the
powers that be and said,

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:57.197
look guys, if we don't do
our own musical very quickly,

00:26:57.197 --> 00:26:58.530
it's going to become irrelevant.

00:26:58.530 --> 00:27:00.480
Because if these
guys get to Broadway,

00:27:00.480 --> 00:27:04.530
there isn't going to be room
for a real Sharknado musical.

00:27:04.530 --> 00:27:07.830
And so we should-- if
we're not doing our own,

00:27:07.830 --> 00:27:10.450
we should just license
the title to them

00:27:10.450 --> 00:27:14.080
and let them put the
real title on it.

00:27:14.080 --> 00:27:15.810
Yeah, so I'd love
to do a musical.

00:27:15.810 --> 00:27:18.430
I started in musical theater
in high school and college.

00:27:18.430 --> 00:27:19.750
MALE SPEAKER: I remember that.

00:27:19.750 --> 00:27:23.380
THUNDER LEVIN: And the material
just lends itself to song.

00:27:23.380 --> 00:27:24.729
MALE SPEAKER: To song, yes.

00:27:24.729 --> 00:27:27.020
I think that's what everybody
thought when they saw it.

00:27:27.020 --> 00:27:28.660
THUNDER LEVIN:
Obviously, and dancing.

00:27:28.660 --> 00:27:33.200
And background dancers dressed
up as sharks, spinning around.

00:27:33.200 --> 00:27:34.290
I mean, it would be great.

00:27:36.880 --> 00:27:40.390
Actually, the one thing I liked
about this shark attack musical

00:27:40.390 --> 00:27:43.040
is they took Tara
Reid's character

00:27:43.040 --> 00:27:47.690
and made her touching
and sympathetic,

00:27:47.690 --> 00:27:50.390
and gave her real
depth, which I had

00:27:50.390 --> 00:27:52.770
done in the original script.

00:27:52.770 --> 00:27:56.289
Because it was actually kind
of a love letter to my ex-wife.

00:27:56.289 --> 00:27:58.080
And it was about how
these two people would

00:27:58.080 --> 00:28:00.430
come together and find
out that they still

00:28:00.430 --> 00:28:04.680
worked well together, and
they still had that chemistry.

00:28:04.680 --> 00:28:07.810
And then I guess when Tara got
cast, that kind of went out

00:28:07.810 --> 00:28:10.440
the window.

00:28:10.440 --> 00:28:12.500
And suddenly she
became a lot bitchier

00:28:12.500 --> 00:28:17.110
and Nova sort of
became the heroine--

00:28:17.110 --> 00:28:19.820
MALE SPEAKER: I see.

00:28:19.820 --> 00:28:23.444
THUNDER LEVIN: Yeah, so I liked
seeing that in the musical.

00:28:23.444 --> 00:28:25.360
MALE SPEAKER: Well, I
hope we get to see that.

00:28:25.360 --> 00:28:26.651
THUNDER LEVIN: So anyhow, yeah.

00:28:26.651 --> 00:28:29.410
If you see Shark Attack
the musical come out,

00:28:29.410 --> 00:28:31.830
it will still be
unauthorized, but go see it,

00:28:31.830 --> 00:28:33.850
because it was really good.

00:28:33.850 --> 00:28:35.990
MALE SPEAKER: All right.

00:28:35.990 --> 00:28:40.980
So were there any scenes,
anything that you really

00:28:40.980 --> 00:28:45.190
regret winding up on
the cutting room floor,

00:28:45.190 --> 00:28:46.500
literally or metaphorically?

00:28:46.500 --> 00:28:47.000
THUNDER LEVIN: There
was nothing that

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:48.250
got on the cutting room floor.

00:28:48.250 --> 00:28:51.320
There were scenes that
we couldn't shoot,

00:28:51.320 --> 00:28:54.470
that just were clearly
beyond our ability.

00:28:54.470 --> 00:28:56.120
In the first movie
there was a scene

00:28:56.120 --> 00:28:58.600
where Beverly Hills
was completely flooded.

00:28:58.600 --> 00:29:00.660
And they were driving
their car through.

00:29:00.660 --> 00:29:04.620
And they ran into this
agent who was on his phone.

00:29:04.620 --> 00:29:06.880
And they yell at him, there
are sharks in the streets.

00:29:06.880 --> 00:29:08.860
And he's like, no kidding,
you wouldn't believe

00:29:08.860 --> 00:29:10.800
this deal I just closed.

00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:14.180
And then he gets eaten.

00:29:14.180 --> 00:29:19.605
And in the second one,
there was a whole act,

00:29:19.605 --> 00:29:26.040
a whole set piece that got
cut, where the wave is washing

00:29:26.040 --> 00:29:30.200
over Manhattan, and
Rockefeller Center skating rink

00:29:30.200 --> 00:29:32.290
gets flooded.

00:29:32.290 --> 00:29:34.730
And they're all thrashing,
trying to get out of the water.

00:29:34.730 --> 00:29:36.080
And the sharks are coming in.

00:29:36.080 --> 00:29:39.160
And that's when Tara
Reid shows up and says,

00:29:39.160 --> 00:29:40.710
hey guys, need a hand?

00:29:40.710 --> 00:29:42.630
And helps rescue them.

00:29:42.630 --> 00:29:45.510
And then they're in
a boat going down

00:29:45.510 --> 00:29:48.310
to the Empire State Building.

00:29:48.310 --> 00:29:52.050
And then the boat-- something
happens to the boat,

00:29:52.050 --> 00:29:56.270
so Finn finds a
hot dog stand car.

00:29:56.270 --> 00:29:58.530
And he turns it upside
down they climb in

00:29:58.530 --> 00:30:02.710
and they surf down Fifth Avenue
in this upturned hot dog cart

00:30:02.710 --> 00:30:03.211
umbrella.

00:30:03.211 --> 00:30:05.334
MALE SPEAKER: Once again,
staying within the bounds

00:30:05.334 --> 00:30:06.060
of the possible.

00:30:06.060 --> 00:30:06.851
THUNDER LEVIN: Yes.

00:30:09.140 --> 00:30:11.240
Yes.

00:30:11.240 --> 00:30:13.040
It makes sense.

00:30:13.040 --> 00:30:17.870
MALE SPEAKER: So
speaking of cars,

00:30:17.870 --> 00:30:19.360
this is a shared
passion of ours,

00:30:19.360 --> 00:30:22.400
you wrote a film titled 200 MPH.

00:30:22.400 --> 00:30:23.490
THUNDER LEVIN: Yes.

00:30:23.490 --> 00:30:25.740
MALE SPEAKER: How do you
feel about self-driving cars?

00:30:25.740 --> 00:30:28.112
THUNDER LEVIN: I don't
care for the idea.

00:30:28.112 --> 00:30:30.070
MALE SPEAKER: I thought
that might be the case.

00:30:30.070 --> 00:30:33.600
THUNDER LEVIN: They can
drive my car when they pry it

00:30:33.600 --> 00:30:34.710
from my cold, dead hands.

00:30:38.726 --> 00:30:40.100
MALE SPEAKER: And
finally I guess

00:30:40.100 --> 00:30:42.800
I wanted to-- since you've
both written and directed

00:30:42.800 --> 00:30:45.933
and both together--
which of those do

00:30:45.933 --> 00:30:48.570
you find more difficult to do?

00:30:48.570 --> 00:30:50.359
Which comes easier?

00:30:50.359 --> 00:30:51.900
THUNDER LEVIN: Well,
I mean directing

00:30:51.900 --> 00:30:55.660
is physically a lot harder.

00:30:55.660 --> 00:30:58.640
I mean, you're working
16 hours a day.

00:30:58.640 --> 00:31:01.090
The stress is extraordinary.

00:31:01.090 --> 00:31:02.870
I've described
directing a feature film

00:31:02.870 --> 00:31:05.680
as the most intense
thing a human being can

00:31:05.680 --> 00:31:08.180
do short of going to war.

00:31:08.180 --> 00:31:10.320
And in fact, a film crew
is organized very much

00:31:10.320 --> 00:31:12.750
like an army.

00:31:12.750 --> 00:31:15.320
So it's a lot harder.

00:31:15.320 --> 00:31:18.590
Writing, you're sitting at home
in your pajamas at a computer.

00:31:18.590 --> 00:31:21.090
What's hard about that?

00:31:21.090 --> 00:31:22.979
When people start
screwing with your work

00:31:22.979 --> 00:31:24.770
and giving you notes
that don't make sense,

00:31:24.770 --> 00:31:27.940
that gets a bit challenging.

00:31:27.940 --> 00:31:29.690
Now, directing is a
lot harder, but I also

00:31:29.690 --> 00:31:31.900
find a lot more fulfilling.

00:31:31.900 --> 00:31:33.470
I was supposed to
direct "Sharknado."

00:31:33.470 --> 00:31:35.620
And in hindsight,
maybe I should have.

00:31:38.300 --> 00:31:46.720
But since it, I've sort
of become re-pigeonholed

00:31:46.720 --> 00:31:47.760
as a writer.

00:31:47.760 --> 00:31:51.670
Whereas I was always a director
first and writer second.

00:31:51.670 --> 00:31:55.290
And so actually, that's
my plan for this year

00:31:55.290 --> 00:31:57.050
is to get back in
the director chair.

00:31:57.050 --> 00:31:58.142
MALE SPEAKER: All right.

00:31:58.142 --> 00:32:04.070
Well, on that note, thank you
very, very much, Thunder Levin.

00:32:04.070 --> 00:32:08.070
And we'll turn it over to the
audience now for questions.

00:32:08.070 --> 00:32:09.686
THUNDER LEVIN: Raise your hands.

00:32:09.686 --> 00:32:11.185
MALE SPEAKER: I
think go to the mic.

00:32:11.185 --> 00:32:13.250
THUNDER LEVIN: Oh, we
have a mic, excellent.

00:32:13.250 --> 00:32:14.510
Oh, and a spotlight.

00:32:14.510 --> 00:32:17.550
Hey, you made the big time.

00:32:17.550 --> 00:32:20.270
AUDIENCE: For "Sharknado
3," who did you imagine

00:32:20.270 --> 00:32:21.790
would play the president?

00:32:21.790 --> 00:32:25.074
And how did you feel about
Mark Cuban's performance there?

00:32:25.074 --> 00:32:26.490
THUNDER LEVIN: I
loved Mark Cuban.

00:32:26.490 --> 00:32:27.600
I thought he was great.

00:32:31.770 --> 00:32:35.590
I wanted-- it was a pipe dream,
but I wanted Harrison Ford

00:32:35.590 --> 00:32:38.050
to play the president.

00:32:38.050 --> 00:32:40.970
That just seemed obvious to me.

00:32:40.970 --> 00:32:43.900
And then the director had an
idea that I thought was great.

00:32:43.900 --> 00:32:45.960
He wanted Bill Murray.

00:32:45.960 --> 00:32:50.000
And the idea was-- I
don't know if any of you

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.340
are old enough to remember
the "Saturday Night Live"

00:32:52.340 --> 00:32:56.040
sketch where Lorne Michaels
comes on and holds up

00:32:56.040 --> 00:33:01.110
a check for $3,000 and asks
the Beatles to reunite,

00:33:01.110 --> 00:33:03.052
and he would pay them $3,000.

00:33:03.052 --> 00:33:05.010
And they could divide it
up anyway they wanted.

00:33:05.010 --> 00:33:06.570
They could give Ringo less.

00:33:06.570 --> 00:33:07.520
Whatever.

00:33:07.520 --> 00:33:11.420
And so he was trying to get
them to come down to the studio

00:33:11.420 --> 00:33:13.730
because he knew they were
all in New York that night

00:33:13.730 --> 00:33:15.460
and perform.

00:33:15.460 --> 00:33:19.130
And so we were going to
do a YouTube video making

00:33:19.130 --> 00:33:21.089
the same pitch to Bill Murray.

00:33:21.089 --> 00:33:22.880
Because you know, he
doesn't have an agent.

00:33:22.880 --> 00:33:25.380
The only way you get
Bill Murray in your movie

00:33:25.380 --> 00:33:27.370
is you call an 800 number.

00:33:27.370 --> 00:33:28.730
You leave a message.

00:33:28.730 --> 00:33:31.370
And you try and intrigue him.

00:33:31.370 --> 00:33:32.530
And he's traveling around--

00:33:32.530 --> 00:33:32.890
MALE SPEAKER: For real?

00:33:32.890 --> 00:33:33.510
THUNDER LEVIN: Yeah.

00:33:33.510 --> 00:33:34.843
He's traveling around the world.

00:33:34.843 --> 00:33:37.510
He doesn't even have a
home address, apparently.

00:33:37.510 --> 00:33:38.940
And he checks his messages.

00:33:38.940 --> 00:33:41.090
And if something sounds
fun to him, he'll do it.

00:33:41.090 --> 00:33:42.980
So we thought if
we did this YouTube

00:33:42.980 --> 00:33:47.170
video it might get to him and
he might be tickled by it.

00:33:47.170 --> 00:33:52.320
But then SyFy wouldn't
let us announce

00:33:52.320 --> 00:33:56.900
that we were doing the film,
or that the director and I were

00:33:56.900 --> 00:34:01.050
involved until they were--
until their PR machine was

00:34:01.050 --> 00:34:03.220
ready to make the announcement.

00:34:03.220 --> 00:34:06.110
And by then it was too late.

00:34:06.110 --> 00:34:08.300
And so we just started
casting around.

00:34:08.300 --> 00:34:10.520
At one point they were
talking about Donald Trump.

00:34:10.520 --> 00:34:12.940
And I said, that's
not realistic at all.

00:34:15.870 --> 00:34:19.270
And Mark Cuban was actually
cast at the very last minute.

00:34:19.270 --> 00:34:21.360
We were shooting in LA.

00:34:21.360 --> 00:34:23.179
He was in New York.

00:34:23.179 --> 00:34:25.560
They got to him
the night before,

00:34:25.560 --> 00:34:26.870
and he said I'd love to do it.

00:34:26.870 --> 00:34:28.000
And they said, well,
the only problem is

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:29.330
we need you tomorrow morning.

00:34:29.330 --> 00:34:30.621
And he said, that's no problem.

00:34:30.621 --> 00:34:31.840
I'll just get on my plane.

00:34:31.840 --> 00:34:33.480
And he was there
the next morning.

00:34:33.480 --> 00:34:35.810
And I thought he
did a great job.

00:34:35.810 --> 00:34:39.969
I asked him at lunch if he ever
thought about running for real.

00:34:39.969 --> 00:34:42.010
And he said, no, there
are way too many skeletons

00:34:42.010 --> 00:34:44.576
in my closet for that.

00:34:44.576 --> 00:34:45.409
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:34:45.409 --> 00:34:46.242
THUNDER LEVIN: Sure.

00:34:48.730 --> 00:34:52.128
MALE SPEAKER: Oh come on,
someone else be brave.

00:34:52.128 --> 00:34:54.544
THUNDER LEVIN: Now what made
you choose to go to that mic?

00:34:54.544 --> 00:34:55.570
AUDIENCE: It's closer.

00:34:55.570 --> 00:34:57.340
THUNDER LEVIN: OK.

00:34:57.340 --> 00:34:59.732
But that was already broken in.

00:34:59.732 --> 00:35:00.940
AUDIENCE: It's true.

00:35:00.940 --> 00:35:05.306
Let's see, so with three
Sharknado movies now,

00:35:05.306 --> 00:35:06.680
and there's going
to be a fourth.

00:35:06.680 --> 00:35:07.740
THUNDER LEVIN: There is.

00:35:07.740 --> 00:35:10.320
AUDIENCE: Do you
ever wonder if maybe

00:35:10.320 --> 00:35:12.760
with the space scene
